It's kind of a niche abikity
People with corporate know-how: why won't wizards acknowledge or comment on declining product quality?
Typically poor management.
That seems accurate for WotC, sadly

There are 'reasons' but it almost always comes down to poor management not keeping their eye on the ball, or a corporate structure that rewards kicking problems down the food chain to those who can't actually affect change.

It's probably a perception thing at least partially. If they acknowledge it then they are essentially saying it's true and then everyone knows it as an issue. Where as if they ignore it for now, then the people oblivious to it will stay oblivious and they have time to figure out how they want to handle the situation in the future.
That's just my guess though.
Also poor management is kind of the wotc style, sadly.
I always get the impression that internally wotc still runs things like they're some mom and pop operation
Which can have benefits
That doesn't seem inaccurate.
But it can cause problems when you're NOT a mom and pop operation
Though Glassdoor seems to indicate it comes with all of the problems and none of the benefits.

On that note it's frustrating that they run things like they are the cool kid on the block. "No suits required" mentality. But then they just do scummy things like hide information from players and treat their employees like it's seedy underworld corporate politics with favorites and stuff.
It's been my experience that happens when a company is managed by people who never worked in a real corporate environment and are just kind of faking it
That makes sense
Seems right
I worked most of my 20's for Menards, a Midwest Home Depot-esque company and that's how they worked
It was entirely ran by people who started when it was like three hardware stores and they didn't know how to deal with it being 300 stores in 20 states so they kinda faked it

We rolled out Wifi in around 2002 and it was literally handled by me coming in one morning and having the head of IT say "So you know wireless stuff right? I ordered 4000 Cisco access points that will be here next week. Think you can have that going in a couple months at all the stores?"
I feel like Wotc kinda wings shit like that
I always get the impression it's run like a kingdom where managers build fiefdoms and actively work against each other in a struggle for power.
Dana that wasn't an uncommon attitude about wifi back then since managers didn't quite grasp they were opening up their internal networks to the world.

Oh sure, but at that scale I'd think you'd be less flip about it if you weren't still looking at things like you were small time. They're still using my security setup, too. Ssid's I created still show on my phone in a store :grinning:
tails
Like I'm always shocked drive to work is recorded on his iPhone
I guess maybe being in a car renders anything better moot
He could upgrade to a noise canceling mic but that just not MaRo. Also it's weird he just gets to post whatever he wants without any input from management as far as I can tell.
But it feels so half assed on their side. Maro takes the initiative to record that and nobody thinks to do it right (assuming there's a right way in a car)
And maybe that's for the best that there is no corporate meddling
But it doesn't feel like a choice to allow him to express himself but instead a situation where just nobody is paying attention
AFAIK MaRo has never leaked anything really important, though.
What kind of managerial I put does he need?
Sure, but historically unfiltered communication channels are just asking for it.
Yeah I don't think he needs it but it's odd he doesn't have it if that makes sense
Yeah, that makes sense
Right, it's not about need but more a company of that size typically is more cautious about managing public messaging, etc.
Exactly
It also gives MaRo a certain amount of corporate leverage that most managers wouldn't allow.
MaRo could be a manager if he wanted to, TBF

There's at least one drive to work he had to re-record/ not release because he said something classified in the middle of it. And there was one recently where he let slip Ixalan (talking for Ixidor) a few days before the official announcement.
Sure - but more to the point, if anyone in management slights him, real or not, he has a very public venue to air his grievances.
Sure, but he's also been there so long that, even without the spotlight, it would be hard to oust him.
He's been there so long I think it impossible that he hasn't already been slighted by people plenty of times, and I don't think he's used his platform as a bully pulpit
